2pt"> regarding the Controlled Foreign Companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (CFC)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Finance Company Exemption. When this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> legislation was first introduced, HMRC and HM Treasury appeared to be aware of, and to support, the tax</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">efficient restructuring of functions, assets and risks, to allow existing financing to be held offshore through an overseas finance company. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he latest measures and the guidance suggest that businesses should be wary of transferring any existing loans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to an overseas finance company</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The CBI understands that government is now concerned with the number of existing loans that could be transferred t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o more efficient structures that utili</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">se the finance company</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> partial exemption. However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> this apparent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">change of approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">added</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uncertainty to the new regime.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Promoting simplicity</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On promoting simplicity, the CBI has welcomed the work of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ffice for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">implification</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(OTS) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and supports the need for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> an independent process for reviewing the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">effectiveness of tax laws. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, we believe that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the OTS is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in need of additional resource in order </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">come more</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> effective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at ensuring the recomme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ndations are acted upon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Furtherm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ore, the OTS should be given the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">power to comment on whether proposed legislation meets its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">policy objectives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to strengthen the independent review of tax law</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nteraction between HM Treasury, HMRC and the Parliamentary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Counsel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cause difficulties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the drafting of clear and simple legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This has led to problems in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">moving from a policy conception to well-drafted legislation during</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the drafting stage. This happened with the new CFC regime where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the proposed new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rules resulted in extremely complex draft</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legislation despite an effective and productive consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and clear policy articulation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also a recurring annual problem with the time-restricted Finance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Bill process. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC is currently studying these is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sues, but it is important that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he quality of legislative drafting does not undermine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">policy development.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Greater scrutiny</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">roducing tax legislation in draft to allow for pre-legislative scrutiny is welcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. However,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> policy makers and HMRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be availa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ble to discuss the proposals with affected parties.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It has been noted that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at times</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> HMRC can defer </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> decision to the "policy makers"</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> yet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> some CBI members report being unable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to meet or make representations to th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">policy makers. There are some </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">exceptions to this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or exam</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ple, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the team responsible for Missing Trader Fraud should be applauded for their open dialogue with taxpayers and their willingness to learn and seek outside input. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Supporting transparency</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e welcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overnment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o provide more information on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">costing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">policies. However, m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ore needs to be done to strengthen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HM Treasury and HMRC’s tax economics expertise and increase the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">use of dynamic effects of tax rates on tax revenues. Full dynamic tax</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">analysis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which forecasts the effects of businesses’ reactions to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">incentives created by policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">strengthen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support move</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> towards a more economically efficient tax</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">system. When comprehensive dynamic analysis has taken place,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with HMRC’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 2012 analysis of the top rate of personal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">income tax, the analysis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overturned conventional wisdom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">higher tax rates automatically raise significantly more revenue. Full</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dynamic analysis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be introduced for all major taxes to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assess the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">relationsh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ip between tax policies and economic activity. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The CBI supports a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> transparent, methodical process for changing tax laws in a way that engages all stakeholders, minimises surprises</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and ensures legislation is stress tested before becoming law. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">usiness </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y seeks </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">clarity and certainty </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enable them to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">develop business plans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and make investment decisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> therefore w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hen it comes to tax policy, openness should become the default position of HM Treasury.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">While the CBI acknowledges</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and applauds the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> huge strides</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have been made by the government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in achieving</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a more transparent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tax policy development </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">process, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">number</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and timing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of consultations has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sometimes been difficult for business to manage. We expect that other stakeholder</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, including HMRC and HM </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Treasury, have equally been challenged by the increased volume in work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The government should seek to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">continually</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> improve its consultation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">processes, for example, by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> deploying web-based consultation tools with appropriate controls and differentiation for k</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ey stakeholders, as the European Commission does, or carry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> out a greater number of informal consultations.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Additional comments on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Taxation of Partnerships</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some additional views </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have been</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> raised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by CBI members on the taxation of partner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ships and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">while these do not represent consensus comments of the CBI Tax Committee, we feel that they are important to share these as part of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Economic Affairs Committee’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> enquiry.</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Disguised remuneration – design of legislation and economic impact</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">need for these proposals in Finance Bill 2014 results directly from the discrepancy in tax treatment between</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Limited Liability Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LLPs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and general partnerships (GPs) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arising</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from the specific tax legislation which was introduced when LLPs became available in 2000.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If the rules relating to GPs had been directly applied to LLPs at this time, the playing field between the two types of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">body corporate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would always have been level </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and the door would never have opened to those who seeking to use that rule solely to reduce tax.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If the policy objective is to level the playing field between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">GPs and LLPs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> then all that is needed is to change the deficient legislation to remove the pre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sumption that members are partners.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This would allow the law to revert back to the previous position – namely that an individual’s status (partner or employee) was to be assessed by reference to the tests established by case law.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposed legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">serious potential consequences for an industry sector – professional services - which is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">clearly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">important to the UK’s economy. Furthermore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> this is at a time when many small and medium-sized UK law firms are struggling to raise bank funding. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Simply pu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the impact of these “disguised remuneration” arrangements is to increase tax cost but also to accelerate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">payment of tax so as to collect tax in 2014</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that relates to two years of trading</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We fear that for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK professional business</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ause significant difficulty, especially given the economic environment against which the changes are being implemented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. We are particularly concerned about the timescale of implementation (April 2014)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which provides </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">insufficient time to arrange alterna</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tive sources of funding for those businesses. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It appear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that this economic impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> may not have been fully</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> assessed in advising </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ministers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, perhaps underestimating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the number of firms impacted if the test ‘thresholds’ are set as proposed.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Many firms wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ll have to re-design their partner remuneration and capital structures in order to fit within these rules before April 2014, which will distract from business growth. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 28.35pt 12pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Profit allocation in mixed partnerships</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The second set of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposed new rules penalis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es partnerships with mixed membership </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">both individuals and companies for example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The mixed partnership proposals of the disguised remuneration provisions are very broad, and are likely to affect many legitimate structures, in addition to those that are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">specifically targeted. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In particular, they run counter to other current legislative and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regulatory initiatives, including the liberalisation of the practice of law through so-called Alternative Business Structures. These structures facilitate non-lawyer ex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ternal investment into the legal profession.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whether or not a business is caught by the rules is not determined by a test of commercial motivation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nstead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it is to be assessed by a test of whether or not it is “reasonable to suppose” that the company’s share of profits from the partnership is attributable to the individual partner’s “power to enjoy” it.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> We can see how this test </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is intended to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">work to captu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re inappropriate tax-motivated structures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. However, we are concerned </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that it leaves some genuine, commercial structures and practices in a position of great uncertainty given the highly subjective nature of the test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the lack of any guidance as to how </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it is to be interpreted and applied by HMRC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It seem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that the policy intention </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> address where mixed partnership business structure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> manipulated to extract profits at a low </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(or no) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tax</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rate through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> complex and/or artificial arrangements has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">con</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">siderably</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> widened</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This results in situations being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">attack</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where the only tax advantage is a timing difference. This seems to be as a result of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">very</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> narrow view of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">what constitutes aggressive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tax avoidance. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/193239/Corporation_tax_road_map.pdf </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a